\begin_layout Standard

\change_deleted 1469408620 1668189907
The only difference between the two types of TIM is that the first one has
 a single channel and there is a direct calculation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta t$
\end_inset

, while the second one has two channels, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta t$
\end_inset

 is calculated by making the difference between the timestamps provided
 by each channel.
 Therefore, it's clear that by making the difference between two channels
 of a TIMESTAMP-type TIM, a START/STOP-type TIM is obtained.
 On the other hand, using a START/STOP-type TIM having the START event as
 the power-on instant of the system is equivalent to having one channel
 of a TIMESTAMP-type TIM.
\change_inserted 1469408620 1668191399
If a system capable of measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 physical events is required, a TIMESTAMP-type TIM would simply be characterized
 by a number of channels and outputs equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, a START/STOP-type TIM would need 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 START/STOP pairs behaving as 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 START/STOP-type TIMs.
 However, for the sake of compactness, all the STARTs are generally merged
 into a single START signal, thus requiring just one single connector for
 it and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 connectors for the STOP signals.
 This setup is generally used since it is compatible with the majority of
 time-resolved experiments, where one excitation event is provided to the
 material under-study, and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 output events are triggered.
