\begin_layout Paragraph

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668178519
Ring Delay-Line TDC, RDL-TDC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668182969
The Ring Delay-Line TDC (RDL-TDC) relies on a closed-loop delay-line structure,
 acting as a controlled clock generator (ring-oscillator) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "8303944"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The clock generator uses 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{B}$
\end_inset

 delay units, with a propagation delay equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{P},$
\end_inset

 with the START and the STOP signals acting as control units; then, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{B}$
\end_inset

 latches are used to sample the state of the delay-line during the transitions
 of the generated clock signal.
 Let's see in detail the operation of the RDL-TDC.
 Firstly, when START and STOP both have a 'low' logical level, the generated
 clock signal keeps a 'high' value; then, as soon as START switches to '1',
 the clock generator acts as a ring oscillator, providing a clock signal
 with a certain period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{CLK}$
\end_inset

.
 The battery of latches samples the delay-line during the transitions of
 the clock signal, thus providing the time information (i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{F}$
\end_inset

).
 Basically, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{F}$
\end_inset

 is the number of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

ones
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zeros
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (depending if the generated clock signal is in its 'high' or 'low' half-period,
 respectively) in the generated thermometric code, representing the number
 of transitions in half of a clock period.
 Once also the STOP signal transits to '1', the clock signal holds a 'high'
 logical value, and the sampled data is provided at the output.
 The final time measurement will be equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{M}=N_{F}\cdot LSB\label{eq:meas_asic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668180563
where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
LSB=t_{P}\label{eq:res_asic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668180791
On the other hand, the FSR is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
FSR=N_{B}\cdot t_{P}\label{eq:fsr_asic}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668182024
thus showing the same trade-off of the other DL-TDCs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\change_inserted 1469408620 1668180743
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:TDL-TDC-implemented-in"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows the structure and the working principle of this architecture.
\end_layout

